in a blitz setting.

10
00:00:37,560 --> 00:00:39,845
The best move here is
for White to take the Pawn;

11
00:00:39,870 --> 00:00:42,665
I did not take the Pawn,
because I was afraid of the

12
00:00:42,690 --> 00:00:46,595
tactical complications that would ensue.
Instead I played the very quiet move

13
00:00:46,620 --> 00:00:48,701
e3, and then we just play chess.

14
00:00:49,620 --> 00:00:53,555
So he checks me; I block with
the Bishop; he takes; I take.

15
00:00:53,580 --> 00:00:57,540
I liked the exchange because it
gives me a free developing move.

16
00:00:58,740 --> 00:01:02,350
He does not take the Pawn;
instead he plays ... d6.

17
00:01:03,150 --> 00:01:06,810
I develop my Bishop,
and he trades the Pawn.

18
00:01:07,560 --> 00:01:11,223
He checks me. Again, free
development for me: I'll take it.

19
00:01:12,330 --> 00:01:15,844
And at this point, he
brings out his Bishops.

20
00:01:15,869 --> 00:01:19,020
And now he's going for the attack,
even though it's not really justified.

21
00:01:19,770 --> 00:01:22,490
He's trying to pile
up on my Knight here.

22
00:01:23,040 --> 00:01:24,755
He's got it pinned
against the Queen,

23
00:01:24,780 --> 00:01:27,933
and he also has a pin against
the King; but I just castle,

24
00:01:28,590 --> 00:01:32,580
and I'm gonna bring
a Rook to the center;

25
00:01:34,194 --> 00:01:36,927
and his Queen's going to
be in some trouble,

26
00:01:36,952 --> 00:01:38,513
pinned against the King.

27
00:01:38,538 --> 00:01:40,300
And so, I like my position here.

28
00:01:41,730 --> 00:01:44,018
He takes I take back.

29
00:01:44,043 --> 00:01:46,900
And now he makes a big
mistake. He had to castle.

30
00:01:48,836 --> 00:01:53,042
He had to get out of
the center with his King.

31
00:01:54,210 --> 00:02:00,515
What he's done now is, he's allowed
me the chance of exploiting this

32
00:02:00,540 --> 00:02:03,725
tactic where I go after his
King, and his Queen's in the way;

33
00:02:03,750 --> 00:02:08,229
but, but, first to
prepare it I do Bf3,

34
00:02:08,254 --> 00:02:11,073
and that puts an
attack on the b-pawn.

35
00:02:12,360 --> 00:02:14,839
So I'm threatening to pin
his Queen; I'm threatening his

36
00:02:14,864 --> 00:02:22,225
b-pawn; the only move which
protects both is to castle long.

37
00:02:23,675 --> 00:02:25,256
Uh, this is not the best move.

38
00:02:26,700 --> 00:02:31,835
So now I've got some extra space on the
queen side because my pawns are advanced;

39
00:02:31,860 --> 00:02:34,393
I've got the Bishop already
trained on the Queenside;

40
00:02:34,418 --> 00:02:37,170
my Knight and my Queen
can easily get there; I can

41
00:02:37,170 --> 00:02:40,865
push the a-pawn; this is all
playing out very well for me.

42
00:02:42,540 --> 00:02:46,499
But before I do that I moved the Rook to
e1. Why? Because when I moved the Rook

43
00:02:46,499 --> 00:02:50,130
to e1, his Queen is under attack, and
there's only one way to save it: and

44
00:02:50,130 --> 00:02:52,060
that's to move the Queen back.

45
00:02:54,660 --> 00:02:58,475
And this is improving the
position of my Rook, and

46
00:02:58,500 --> 00:03:02,195
"de-improving" the position of
his Queen. So that's what I did.

47
00:03:02,220 --> 00:03:06,815
Then I bring out the Queen, and
I'm piling up on this pawn here,

48
00:03:06,840 --> 00:03:08,981
threatening mate.

49
00:03:09,006 --> 00:03:14,195
He's forced to weaken his - I say

50
00:03:14,220 --> 00:03:18,215
"Kingside." It's not really the
Kingside; it's the side where his King is,

51
00:03:18,240 --> 00:03:19,565
which is the Queenside.

52
00:03:19,590 --> 00:03:23,370
So he's weakening the pawns in front of his
